      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER IV: TAX STRATEGY</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-tsp-section-title">Roth vs <em>Traditional</em> TSP</h2>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-tsp-body">The choice between Roth and traditional TSP contributions is one of the most important decisions federal employees face. The right choice depends on your current tax bracket, expected retirement income, and overall tax strategy.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-glass-card">
        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 3rem;">
          <div>
            <h3 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Traditional TSP</h3>
            <ul style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6; list-style: none; padding: 0;">
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">✓ Contributions reduce current taxable income</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">✓ Growth is tax-deferred</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">× Withdrawals are fully taxable</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0;">× Required minimum distributions at age 73</li>
            </ul>
            <p style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; margin-top: 1rem; font-style: italic;">Best for: High current income, expect lower tax bracket in retirement</p>
          </div>
          
          <div>
            <h3 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Roth TSP</h3>
            <ul style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6; list-style: none; padding: 0;">
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">× Contributions made with after-tax dollars</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">✓ Growth is completely tax-free</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">✓ Withdrawals are tax-free in retirement</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0;">✓ No required minimum distributions</li>
            </ul>
            <p style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; margin-top: 1rem; font-style: italic;">Best for: Early career, expect higher tax bracket in retirement</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-tsp-body">Many financial advisors recommend a "tax diversification" approach — contributing to both Roth and traditional accounts to give you flexibility in retirement. This is especially valuable for federal employees who have predictable FERS pension income and can strategically withdraw from different account types based on their tax situation each year.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-stats-grid">
        <div class="fed-ed-stat">
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-number">22%</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-label">Current Fed Tax Bracket</span>
        </div>
        <div class="fed-ed-stat">
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-number">12%</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-label">Typical Retirement Bracket</span>
        </div>
        <div class="fed-ed-stat">
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-number">$30,000</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-label">Tax-Free Roth Growth (20 yrs)</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
    
    <!-- WITHDRAWAL PLANNING -->
    <section id="withdrawals" class="fed-ed-tsp-section">
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER V: WITHDRAWALS</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-tsp-section-title">Retirement <em>Withdrawal</em> Strategy</h2>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-tsp-body">How you withdraw from your TSP in retirement is just as important as how you invested during your career. The TSP offers four withdrawal options, each with different implications for taxes, flexibility, and estate planning.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-glass-card">
        <table class="fed-ed-comparison-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Withdrawal Option</th>
              <th>Flexibility</th>
              <th>Income Guarantee</th>
              <th>Estate Benefits</th>
              <th>Best For</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Monthly Installments</strong></td>
              <td>High</td>
              <td>None</td>
              <td>Remaining balance</td>
              <td>Most retirees</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>TSP Annuity</strong></td>
              <td>None</td>
              <td>Lifetime</td>
              <td>Limited</td>
              <td>Income certainty priority</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Single Payment</strong></td>
              <td>Maximum</td>
              <td>None</td>
              <td>Full control</td>
              <td>Rolling to IRA</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="highlight">
              <td><strong>Combination</strong></td>
              <td>Medium</td>
              <td>Partial</td>
              <td>Partial</td>
              <td>Balanced approach</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-tsp-body">Federal employees who separate from service in the year they turn 55 or older can access their TSP without the 10% early withdrawal penalty. This is a valuable benefit not available in most private sector 401(k) plans.</p>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-tsp-body">The key is coordinating your TSP withdrawals with your FERS annuity, Social Security, and any other retirement income to minimize taxes and maximize cash flow throughout retirement.</p>
    </section>
    
    <!-- ROLLOVER DECISIONS -->
    <section id="rollover" class="fed-ed-tsp-section">
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER VI: ROLLOVER ANALYSIS</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-tsp-section-title">Keep TSP or <em>Roll</em> to IRA?</h2>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-tsp-body">One of the biggest decisions facing federal retirees is whether to keep their TSP or roll it to an IRA. Both options have compelling advantages, and the right choice depends on your specific situation and priorities.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-glass-card">
        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 3rem;">
          <div>
            <h3 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Keep TSP</h3>
            <ul style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6; list-style: none; padding: 0;">
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">✓ Extremely low expense ratios (0.057%)</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">✓ Unique G Fund access</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">✓ Age 55 penalty-free access</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">✓ Strong fraud protection</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0;">× Limited investment options</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          
          <div>
            <h3 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Roll to IRA</h3>
            <ul style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6; list-style: none; padding: 0;">
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">✓ Unlimited investment options</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">✓ Greater withdrawal flexibility</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">✓ Better estate planning features</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">✓ Roth conversion opportunities</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0;">× Higher fees and complexity</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-tsp-body">There's no requirement to choose one or the other. Many federal retirees benefit from a partial rollover strategy — keeping some money in the TSP for its unique benefits while rolling a portion to an IRA for greater investment flexibility and estate planning advantages.</p>
    </section>
    
    <!-- OPTIMIZATION STRATEGIES -->
    <section id="optimization" class="fed-ed-tsp-section">
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER VII: OPTIMIZATION</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-tsp-section-title">Advanced TSP <em>Strategies</em></h2>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-tsp-body">Beyond the basics of contribution limits and fund allocation, there are advanced strategies that can significantly enhance your TSP's value over time. These techniques require careful planning but can add thousands to your retirement security.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-glass-card">
        <h3 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Advanced Optimization Techniques</h3>
        
        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 2rem;">
          <div>
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #F09F54; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Contribution Timing</h4>
            <ul style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6;">
              <li>Front-load contributions for maximum growth time</li>
              <li>Coordinate with FERS pension timing</li>
              <li>Maximize catch-up and super catch-up contributions</li>
              <li>Strategic Roth/traditional mixing</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #F09F54; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Withdrawal Sequencing</h4>
            <ul style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6;">
              <li>Coordinate with FERS and Social Security</li>
              <li>Tax-efficient withdrawal ordering</li>
              <li>Roth conversion ladders</li>
              <li>Asset location optimization</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-tsp-body">The TSP's low fees make it an excellent accumulation vehicle, but its withdrawal options are more limited than IRAs. Many federal employees benefit from a hybrid approach — maximizing TSP contributions during their career, then strategically rolling portions to IRAs for more flexible retirement income planning.</p>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-tsp-body">With the average federal employee having $780,000 in their TSP at retirement, proper withdrawal strategy can mean the difference between running out of money and leaving a significant legacy.</p>
    </section>
  </main>
</section>

<!-- FAQ SECTION -->
<section class="fed-ed-faq">
  <div class="fed-ed-faq-inner">
    <div>
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER VIII: COMMON QUESTIONS</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-tsp-section-title">TSP Planning <em>FAQ</em></h2>
      <p class="fed-ed-tsp-body">Everything you need to know about maximizing your Thrift Savings Plan.</p>
      <div style="margin-top: 2rem;">
        <a href="/contact/" class="fed-ed-btn-primary">Optimize My TSP</a>
      </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="fed-ed-faq-accordion">
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">Should I max out my TSP contributions?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">At minimum, you should contribute at least 5% of your salary to capture the full agency match — the government's automatic 1% plus dollar-for-dollar matching on the next 3% of your salary, and 50 cents on the dollar for the next 1%. Beyond that, maxing out your TSP (up to $24,500 in 2026, or $32,000 if age 50+) depends on your overall financial situation, other savings goals, and whether you have high-interest debt. The TSP offers extremely low fees and excellent tax benefits, making it one of the best places to save for retirement.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">Should I contribute to Roth or traditional TSP?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">Traditional TSP contributions reduce your taxable income now but are taxed when withdrawn. Roth TSP contributions are made with after-tax dollars but grow and can be withdrawn tax-free in retirement. Generally, Roth makes more sense if you expect to be in a higher tax bracket in retirement, or if you're early in your career with lower current income. Traditional makes sense if you're in a high tax bracket now and expect lower income in retirement. Many federal employees benefit from a mix of both — we can model your specific situation to determine the optimal split.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">Should I roll my TSP to an IRA when I retire?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">The TSP has incredibly low expense ratios and offers unique benefits like the G Fund. However, an IRA rollover provides more investment options, greater withdrawal flexibility, and potentially better estate planning features. If you separate from service in the year you turn 55 or older, the TSP also allows penalty-free withdrawals before age 59½. Whether to keep your TSP or roll it to an IRA depends on your investment preferences, withdrawal needs, and overall estate planning goals. There's no one-size-fits-all answer — we evaluate your specific situation to make the right recommendation.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">What are my TSP withdrawal options?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">TSP offers four main withdrawal options: (1) Single payment of your entire balance, (2) Monthly installments based on your choice of amount or life expectancy, (3) Purchase of a TSP life annuity for guaranteed monthly income, or (4) A combination of these options. Each has different tax and income implications. Monthly installments offer flexibility but no income guarantee. Life annuities provide guaranteed income but no access to principal. Most retirees benefit from a strategic combination, often keeping some TSP funds for growth while taking systematic withdrawals coordinated with FERS and Social Security.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">How do L Funds work and should I use them?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">L Funds (Lifecycle Funds) are professionally managed portfolios that automatically adjust their allocation to become more conservative as you approach retirement. Each L Fund has a target retirement year (like L 2030, L 2040, etc.) and rebalances quarterly. They're designed as a simple, set-it-and-forget-it option. L Funds work well for hands-off investors who want automatic rebalancing, but they may not account for your specific situation — like whether you have a FERS pension, other savings, or a risk tolerance that differs from the average. We can evaluate whether an L Fund suits your needs or if a custom allocation makes more sense.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<script>
(function() {
  document.querySelectorAll('.fed-ed-faq-trigger').forEach(function(btn) {
    btn.addEventListener('click', function() {
      var item = this.closest('.fed-ed-faq-item');
      var isOpen = item.classList.contains('active');
      
      // Close all items
      document.querySelectorAll('.fed-ed-faq-item').forEach(function(el) {
        el.classList.remove('active');
      });
      
      // Open clicked item if it wasn't already open
      if (!isOpen) {
        item.classList.add('active');
      }
    });
  });
  
  // Smooth scroll for navigation links
  document.querySelectorAll('.fed-ed-tsp-nav a').forEach(function(link) {
    link.addEventListener('click', function(e) {
      e.preventDefault();
      const targetId = this.getAttribute('href');
      const targetElement = document.querySelector(targetId);
      if (targetElement) {
        targetElement.scrollIntoView({
          behavior: 'smooth',
          block: 'start'
        });
      }
    });
  });
})();
</script>